05183nam a22011175i 9780520924475DE-B159720220524034747.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220524t19991999cau    fo  d z      eng d  a2021696299  a97805209244757 a10.1525/97805209244752doi  a(DE-B1597)521051  a(OCoLC)45731629  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA00aDT509.45.M34 4aDT509.45.M34bS37 1999eb 7aSCI0300002bisacsh04a338.1/0966512211 aSchroeder, Richard A., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aShady Practices :bAgroforestry and Gender Politics in The Gambia /cRichard A. Schroeder. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[1999] 4cÂ©1999  a1 online resource (206 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCalifornia Studies in Critical Human Geography ;v50 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aShady Practices is a revealing analysis of the gendered political ecology brought about by conflicting local interests and changing developmental initiatives in a West African village. Between 1975 and 1985, while much of Africa suffered devastating drought conditions, Gambian women farmers succeeded in establishing hundreds of lucrative communal market gardens. In less than a decade, the women's incomes began outstripping their husbands' in many areas, until a shift in development policy away from gender equity and toward environmental concerns threatened to do away with the social and economic gains of the garden boom. Male landholders joined forestry personnel in attempts to displace the gardens and capture women's labor for the irrigation of male-controlled tree crops.This carefully documented microhistory draws on field experience spanning more than two decades and the insights of disciplines ranging from critical human geography to development studies. Schroeder combines the "success story" of the market gardens with a cautionary tale about the aggressive pursuit of natural resource management objectives, however well intentioned. He shows that questions of power and social justice at the community level need to enter the debates of policymakers and specialists in environment and development planning.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aAgroforestryxGambiaxAlkalikunda. 0aAgroforestryzGambiazAlkalikunda. 0aDivision of laborxGambiaxAlkalikunda. 0aDivision of laborzGambiazAlkalikunda. 0aForest ecologyxGambiaxAlkalikunda. 0aForest ecologyzGambiazAlkalikunda. 0aMandingo (African people)xAgriculture. 0aMandingo (African people)xSocial conditions. 0aPatriarchyxGambiaxAlkalikunda. 0aPatriarchyzGambiazAlkalikunda. 0aSex rolexPolitical aspectsxGambiaxAlkalikunda. 0aSex rolexPolitical aspectszGambiazAlkalikunda. 0aWomen, MandingoxEconomic conditions. 7aSCIENCE / Earth Sciences / Geography.2bisacsh  a1970s.  a1980s.  aacademic.  acommunity.  acrops.  acultural studies.  adrought.  aeconomics.  aeconomy.  aenvironmental.  aenvironmentalist.  afarmers.  afarming.  afemale farmers.  aforestry.  agambia.  agardening.  agender politics.  agender roles.  agender studies.  ageography.  ahuman development.  airrigation.  alandowners.  amicrohistory.  anatural disaster.  apolitical.  apolitics.  ascholarly.  asmall town.  asocial justice.  avillage.  awest africa.  awomens labor.  aworking women.  aworld history.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z978311063534840uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052092447540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520924475423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520924475/original  a978-3-11-063534-8  University of California Pre